City Council President Jim Ferlo said
that he expects the mayor to support his list
of proposed changes to the Oakland area,
which includes a resolution of the Bigelow
Boulevard issue.

Because Mayor Tom Murphy has
strongly supported closing Bigelow and
Ferlo has intensely opposed a closing, a
compromise would be a landmark move
between the two.

Despite their past disagreement on the
issue, Ferlo seemed optimistic yesterday
about obtaining Murphy’s public support.

“He was very supportive [of the pro-
posed list] in private,” said Ferlo. “We are
now waiting for the mayor’s public sup-
port.”

If Murphy approves the list, Ferlo said
it will deﬁnitely “resolve the Bigelow
issue.”

He stated that his list outlines 30 to 40
issues he would like to resolve in and around
the Oakland community, but he refused to
comment in any detail.

“The proposal is not only about
Bigelow, but important related issues to the
Forbes and Fifth Avenue corridor,” said
Ferlo. “People must view the issue of
Bigelow as a way  to improve the com-
dor.”

Ferlo said not enough attention has

