As spring break approaches,
thoughts of sipping drinks on the
beach or shushing down the ski
slopes may sound much more
appealing than brushing up your
resume for career prospects, but for
many Pitt students, the real world
arrives in two months.

Fortunately, the Monroeville
ExpoMart will be hosting a job fair
on March 6 to ease the minds of
worried Western Pennsylvanian job-
seekers.

The event has been planned by
the ExpoMart exclusively for 32
Western Pennsylvania colleges and
universities.

“The job fair offers an opportu-
nity for students to make contacts
with prospective employers,” said
job fair promoter Jim McClanahan.

McClanahan anticipates 141
businesses, primarily from the mid-
Atlantic region, will attend and
answer prospective employees’
questions ranging from career
moves to employment potential.

The event, which brought in
nearly 1,200 students last year, is
expected to grow this year and will

 

include a wider range of companies.
According to McClanahan, the
fields covered by the fair will range
from law enforcement to engineer-
ing and everything in between.

Caren Marcus, the internship
coordinator for the English depart-
ment said the fair is a great opportu-
nity.—
“The benefits of a job fair are
numerous,” said Marcus. “It gives
students ideas on career moves.”

Marcus also said the fair is a
great forum to dress up and talk to
adults for interviewing practice.

McClanahan offered a little
advice to students thinking about
heading to the fair as part of their
spring break.

“If you plan on visiting 15
booths, then bring more than 15
resumes,” said McClanahan. He
also advised students to dress as
though they were interviewing for a
job.

The job fair doors will open at
the ExpoMart at 9 a.m. and the fair
will run until 4 p.m. Interested stu-
dents can call the center at 851-8100
for more information. Those attend-
ing should bring their school I.D.s.

