Lacrosse pitches l2-O shutout  

 

last time Dave Travis
pitched a shutout, he was a sopho-
more at Upper St. Clair high school.

However, with the help of a
tough Pitt defense, Travis shut out

The

Wheeling College last Friday
evening in a 12-0 blowout.

Travis, the senior goaltender for
the Pitt men’s lacrosse team, faced
only seven shots on goal to complete
the shutout.

“It was great to get the shutout,”
Travis said. “It’s a great feeling, and
everyone came back to play defense.
Coach Neft wanted to pull me in the
last quarter, but I wanted to stay in
and get the blank.”

The Panthers also put on an
offensive show, with eight different
players scoring in the blowout.

However, the story of the game
was Pitt’s defense.

“Our defense was tremendous,”
Head Coach Gary Neft said. “They
played as well as a defense could
play. They only allowed Travis to
face several tough shots. This was a
great bounce back game, after that
tough loss to Ohio University.”

The Panthers also got a boost

Tuesday, February 25, ‘I997 ’

from the return of junior Tom Evans,

who was sick for the Ohio U game, ‘

and freshman Dave Corrado, who

was stuck in New York because of

snow.
Sophomore

attacker Matt

Hopelmazian led the Panthers with ’

four goals and Rob Spellman netted
two goals. Six other players scored a
goal apiece for Pitt.

“Our last loss got us fired up,”
sophomore defenseman Brian
Pasquini said. “We came out and got
the job done, and our team played
well. Our offense was exciting and
we created a lot of turnovers. It was
a real team effort.”

The victory also saw the return
of the Pitt attackers. In the loss to
Ohio University, the Panther attack-
ers scored only one of the eight
goals.

“Our attackers played well,” Neft
said. “They scored eight out of our
12 goals.”

The win raises the Panthers
record to 2-1 overall and 1-0 in the
Allegheny North section of the
National Collegiate Lacrosse
League.

The Panthers will host Allegheny
this Thursday night at 7:00 p.m. at
Pitt Stadium. -

